  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="KT351-kilavi">talaimakaṉ tamar varaivoṭu vantavaḻi “namar avarkku varaivu nērār kollō”
          eṉṟu añciya talaimakaṭkut tōḻi varaivu malintatu. </p>


        <p xml:lang="en">The confidante rejoicing about marriage to HER, who was
          afraid “will our people not grant marriage to him?”, as HIS people came with [the offer
          of] marriage. </p>
      </div>

      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="KT351">
          <l> vaḷaiyō yuvanticiṉ viraivuṟu koṭuntā</l>
          <l> ḷaḷaivā ḻalavaṉ kūrukir varitta</l>
          <l> vīrmaṇaṉ malirneṟi citaiya viḻumeṉa</l>
          <l> vurumicaip puṇari yuṭaitarun tuṟaivark</l>
          <l> kurimai ceppiṉar namarē viriyalarp</l>
          <l> puṉṉai yōṅkiya pulālañ cēri</l>
          <l> yiṉṉakai yāyat tārō</l>
          <l> ṭiṉṉu maṟṟōviv vaḻuṅka lūrē.</l>


        </lg>

        <lg xml:lang="en">
          <l>O you bangled one, <note place="foot">There are a few, though not many cases of vocatives starting as sentence or even a poem (not counting the formulaic prelude <term xml:lang="ta"> amma vāḻi tōḻi </term>), some of them even unmarked metonymies (cf. KT 209.4, 358.2). </note> rejoice:</l>
          <l>Our people granted [your] possession</l>
          <l rend="indent8">to the man from the ghat,</l>
          <l rend="indent">where waves with thunder-sound are breaking sweetly,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">so that they destroy, by flooding the moist sand, the ways scratched</l>
          <l rend="indent2">by the sharp nails of quick, bent-legged crabs living in holes.</l>
          <l>This noisy village, [is it] like that even now,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">with pleasantly jesting attendants,</l>
          <l rend="indent">in the fish-reeking quarter, where broad-blossomed Puṉṉai trees</l>
          <l rend="indent6">have become high?</l>


        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
